===Verb===
{{en-verb|shears|shearing|sheared|past2=shore|shorn|past_ptc2=sheared}}

# To [[cut]], originally with a sword or other bladed weapon, now usually with [[shears]], or as if using shears.
#* '''1819''', Walter Scott, ''Ivanhoe'':
#*: So trenchant was the Templar’s weapon, that it '''shore''' asunder, as it had been a willow twig, the tough and plaited handle of the mace, which the ill-fated Saxon reared to parry the blow, and, descending on his head, levelled him with the earth.
#* Shakespeare
#*: the golden tresses {{...}} were '''shorn''' away
# To [[remove]] the [[fleece]] from a [[sheep]] etc by [[clipping]].
# {{lb|en|physics}} To [[deform]] because of forces pushing in opposite directions.
# {{lb|en|Scotland}} To [[reap]], as grain.
#: {{rfquotek|Jamieson}}
# {{lb|en|figurative}} To [[deprive]] of [[property]]; to [[fleece]].

